Have we finally, at long last, reached the Paramount Global endgame? It=E2=
=80=99s increasingly looking that way. On Friday, word leaked that the spec=
ial committee of the Paramount board of directors had recommended to Shari =
Redstone the deal proposed by a consortium led by David Ellison of Skydance=
 Media and Gerry Cardinale of RedBird Capital, after the group sweetened it=
s bid over the course of the last week. On Sunday afternoon, the Journal re=
ported ( https://www.wsj.com/business/deals/revised-skydance-offer-gives-pa=
ramount-shareholders-opportunity-to-cash-out-at-15-a-share-3c2a16b1?st=3Dhr=
gxqf2qat5x1ph&reflink=3Darticle_copyURL_share&utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%286%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F8=
%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c6=
0617da42abd12a ) that the sweetener included an offer to buy nonvoting shar=
es at $15 each, or the option to roll them into the new deal, a premium of =
about 25 percent to Friday=E2=80=99s
close. But whether the board=E2=80=99s recommendation is good enough for Sh=
ari remains to be seen. She alone is the decider.

In truth, I=E2=80=99ve never seen so much obsessive, minute-to-minute media=
 coverage around a deal with so little actual deal heat from potential buye=
rs. Aside from Skydance/RedBird and Sony/Apollo=E2=80=94both of which have =
seemed somewhat indifferent to the asset at times, and keener to walk away =
than to complete the deal=E2=80=94there ain=E2=80=99t a whole lot of buyer =
interest in Paramount Global. It=E2=80=99s nutty, and I know
I=E2=80=99ve done my part in contributing to the media frenzy. But I find i=
t fascinating from an M&A point of view because it=E2=80=99s been such a bi=
zarre and lengthy process, and Shari could still decide to do nothing at th=
e end of all this mishegas, which has seen the departure of the company=E2=
=80=99s C.E.O. and four of its board members along the way. Shareholders wo=
uld hate it if she walked away at this point, but she=E2=80=99ll probably f=
ace investor lawsuits no matter what she decides. (This is neither investme=
nt nor legal advice.)

Shari could yet buck the conventional wisdom in Hollywood and decide to go =
with the all-cash offer from Sony/Apollo, which is still doing due diligenc=
e on the company after having signed an N.D.A. (Get on with it already!) It=
=E2=80=99s assumed that deal would include about $14 billion for Paramount=
=E2=80=99s equity, which is now trading at a value of $8.3 billion, plus th=
e assumption of its $12.2 billion of net debt. A nice premium for existing =
shareholders,
to be sure, but that=E2=80=99s the end of the story if Shari takes the deal=
=2E Once the company is sold, any upsid=
e goes to the new owners. At least wit=
h Skydance/RedBird, there is the possibility=E2=80=94not without risk, of c=
ourse=E2=80=94that the Paramount stock could double or triple or more, whic=
h would be a nice surprise for the shareholders who decide to stick around.

And I think that=E2=80=99s what most long-suffering Paramount Global shareh=
olders want most of all right now: the chance for a fresh start, after year=
s of watching Shari and her team fritter away billions in value. Remember, =
with the multistep Skydance/RedBird deal, Ellison and Cardinale are promisi=
ng to 1) buy National Amusements Inc., the Redstone holding company, thus t=
aking control of Paramount; 2) inject some $3 billion to reduce Paramount=
=E2=80=99s debt and to offer the non-Redstone shareholders a little somethi=
ng for their stock; 3) steer Paramount to buy Ellison=E2=80=99s Skydance Me=
dia, the Hollywood production company, for
$5 billion in stock; and finally, 4) install a new leadership team, with El=
lison likely running the combined Paramount and Skydance movie studios, and=
 RedBird executives Jeff Shell and Jeff Zucker likely running Paramount Glo=
bal and CBS, respectively.

