Remaining Shari Mysteries

The great mystery of the Ellison/Cardinale deal, of course, is how much the=
y have reduced their offer to Shari and sweetened their offer to the non-Re=
dstone shareholders of Paramount Global and whether they will lower the ask=
ing price for Skydance. It=E2=80=99s not known yet whether Ellison/RedBird =
is sticking to that $5 billion request, or whether they have reduced their =
ask slightly in order to further appeal to the special committee and to Sha=
ri. Nor do we know what kind of sweetener Ellison/RedBird have been cooking=
 up for the nonvoting shareholders of Paramount Global, or how much of this=
 new money might come out of Shari=E2=80=99s hide. (All of them have their =
hands out, that=E2=80=99s for sure.) The Paramount stock has inched up roug=
hly 5 percent since my partner Dylan Byers reported=20
( https://puck.news/newsletter_content/nbcs-sir-charles-fantasies-paramount=
-buzz-beast-belt-tightening/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2=
F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
on Thursday that the special committee was likely to recommend the deal to =
Shari, which has now happened. But team Ellison/RedBird is keeping quiet ab=
out the specifics of their deal, for now.

The most creative part of the Ellison/RedBird deal is that the newly recapi=
talized Paramount Global would remain a public company, the shareholders of=
 which will be the consortium of Ellison/RedBird/KKR et al. and those exist=
ing and future Paramount Global shareholders who decide to take a flier on =
the new management team and the new structure. And why wouldn=E2=80=99t the=
y stick around at this point to see what this group can do?
The Skydance/RedBird group is hoping that the still-public Paramount Global=
 stock price will one day hit somewhere between $30 and $40 a share under t=
he leadership of Ellison and Shell. Is that crazy? It=E2=80=99s speculative=
, for sure, and it=E2=80=99s quite possible the newly recapitalized stock w=
ill never get there. But some may be persuaded by the specter of a new team=
 after years of woeful mismanagement.

If I were a Paramount shareholder, I=E2=80=99d stick around to find out wha=
t Ellison/Shell/Zucker can do with this thing, if that=E2=80=99s the way th=
is ends up. After all, they=E2=80=99ve pretty much put their money where th=
eir mouth is. They don=E2=80=99t make money on either their Paramount stock=
 or on their convertible preferred until the stock goes up, so at least the=
ir economic interests are aligned with yours. But since I=E2=80=99m not a P=
aramount Global shareholder and never have been, we=E2=80=99ll all just hav=
e to wait and see what Shari decides. (Again, not investment advice=E2=80=
=A6)

Could
she give us all her answers on Tuesday, as The Wall Street Journal suggeste=
d, when Paramount holds its annual shareholder meeting? I wouldn=E2=80=99t =
hold my breath. Nobody except for Shari seems to know her timing for a deci=
sion, and those that do know ain=E2=80=99t talking. I doubt Shari even know=
s the precise terms of the revised Ellison/RedBird deal yet, so an answer b=
y Tuesday seems wildly unrealistic. This is a very big decision for her, no=
t one to be rushed into because there happens to be an annual shareholders =
meeting coming up on Zoom. (A spokesman for Shari, Molly Morse, at Kekst CN=
C, declined to elaborate on Shari=E2=80=99s timing.)

