etener included an offer to buy nonvoting shares at $15 each, or the option=
 to roll them into the new deal, a premium of about 25 percent to Friday=E2=
=80=99s close. But whether the board=E2=80=99s recommendation is good enoug=
h for Shari remains to be seen. She alone is the decider. <br/><br/>In trut=
h, I=E2=80=99ve never seen so much obsessive, minute-to-minute media covera=
ge around a deal with so little actual deal <i>heat</i> from potential buye=
rs. Aside from Skydance/RedBird and Sony/Apollo=E2=80=94both of which have =
seemed somewhat indifferent to the asset at times, and keener to walk away =
than to complete the deal=E2=80=94there ain=E2=80=99t a whole lot of buyer =
interest in Paramount Global. It=E2=80=99s nutty, and I know
I=E2=80=99ve done my part in contributing to the media frenzy. But I find i=
t fascinating from an M&amp;A point of view because it=E2=80=99s been such =
a bizarre and lengthy process, and Shari could still decide to do nothing a=
t the end of all this <i>mishegas</i>, which has seen the departure of the =
company=E2=80=99s C.E.O. and four of its board members along the way. Share=
holders would hate it if she walked away at this point, but she=E2=80=99ll =
probably face investor lawsuits no matter what she decides. (This is neithe=
r investment nor legal advice.)<br/><br/>Shari could yet buck the conventio=
